<fr:p>The inductive case, we write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R^{n}=R^{n-1}\oplus  R]]></fr:tex> and take <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F_{0}=R^{n-1}]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M\cap  F_{0}\subseteq  M]]></fr:tex>. Let us call this <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M_{0}=M\cap  F_{0}]]></fr:tex>. By induction <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M_{0}]]></fr:tex> is free, finitely-generated of rank at most <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n-1]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M=M_{0}]]></fr:tex>, then we're done.</fr:p>
<fr:p>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M\neq  M_{0}]]></fr:tex>, then we have to consider some element of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> which generates the rest of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex>. We look at
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[I=\{\alpha \mid \alpha  e_{n}+f_{0}\in  M,f_{0}\in  F_{0}\},]]></fr:tex>
and the claim is that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I\mathrel {\trianglelefteq } R]]></fr:tex> is a nonzero ideal. This is because <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I=(0)]]></fr:tex> iff <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M\subseteq  F_{0}]]></fr:tex>. So <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I\neq (0)]]></fr:tex> is generated by a single nonzero element (since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is a principal ideal domain), say <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I=(\gamma )]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M=M_{0}\oplus  R\omega ]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\omega =e_{n}\gamma +f\in  M]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><html:span
